254
00:23:15,572 --> 00:23:18,598
Why don't we sit down?
Leslie, take the spot right here.

255
00:23:23,747 --> 00:23:26,443
Davie's taking our famous
torture test tomorrow.

256
00:23:26,517 --> 00:23:27,882
- Oh, really?
- Yeah.

257
00:23:27,952 --> 00:23:31,183
And I have a feeling
you're taking yours tonight, Leslie.

258
00:23:36,593 --> 00:23:38,083
Salad. I love salad.

259
00:23:39,663 --> 00:23:40,925
Tomatoes.

260
00:23:42,499 --> 00:23:43,329
Great.

261
00:23:49,273 --> 00:23:52,174
Dr. Sommers tells me
you're into Eastern philosophy.

262
00:23:52,543 --> 00:23:55,137
Yes, I'm sure Dr. Sommers told you that.

263
00:23:55,212 --> 00:23:57,680
When Dr. Sommers tells you
to come to his house...

264
00:23:57,748 --> 00:24:00,615
...to meet his brother
who's into Eastern philosophy...

265
00:24:00,684 --> 00:24:03,312
...you really don't have much choice,
do you?

266
00:24:03,721 --> 00:24:05,814
You're being very inconsiderate, Davie.

267
00:24:05,889 --> 00:24:07,481
My name is David.

268
00:24:10,661 --> 00:24:12,686
And I'm not being inconsiderate.

269
00:24:13,530 --> 00:24:15,464
- I'd better...
- It's all right.

270
00:24:15,532 --> 00:24:18,023
Sit down. Eat your dinner.
Don't mind him.

271
00:24:18,369 --> 00:24:20,769
You don't have to take orders from him.

272
00:24:20,838 --> 00:24:23,864
You can tell him to go to hell.
You can tell me to go to hell.

273
00:24:23,941 --> 00:24:26,808
- I didn't come here to tell...
- I know how you feel.

274
00:24:31,015 --> 00:24:33,347
You seem like a really nice girl.

275
00:24:34,118 --> 00:24:38,214
But for once I'd like to meet a girl
who doesn't know my mother or brother.

276
00:24:38,288 --> 00:24:39,880
The world's full of them.

277
00:24:39,957 --> 00:24:41,515
You have to leave home first.

278
00:24:41,592 --> 00:24:44,686
That's great. "Dr. Considerate" speaks.

279
00:24:45,362 --> 00:24:47,887
Father dies and you take off the same day.

280
00:24:50,300 --> 00:24:51,426
What was I supposed to do?

281
00:24:51,502 --> 00:24:54,130
This isn't the time to bring up
family problems.

282
00:24:54,204 --> 00:24:55,228
I'd better...

283
00:24:55,305 --> 00:24:58,468
It's all right, Leslie.
I'm not ashamed of my family.

284
00:24:59,076 --> 00:25:02,671
You probably have a mother. You wouldn't
turn your back on her in a crisis.

285
00:25:02,746 --> 00:25:04,543
She created the goddamn crisis.

286
00:25:04,615 --> 00:25:06,810
I don't care who created it!

287
00:25:13,991 --> 00:25:16,221
She was crazy about you, Marcus.

288
00:25:16,393 --> 00:25:19,157
Bragging about her brilliant son.
Everything you did.

289
00:25:19,229 --> 00:25:21,493
I know. Everything I did was great.

290
00:25:21,565 --> 00:25:24,295
When I lost, she convinced me
I could've won.

291
00:25:24,368 --> 00:25:25,801
That there's no difference.

292
00:25:25,869 --> 00:25:28,531
I don't think that's so terrible.
Do you, Leslie?

293
00:25:28,605 --> 00:25:29,902
I think it's terrible.

294
00:25:29,973 --> 00:25:31,838
Many people would call it support.

295
00:25:31,909 --> 00:25:35,072
When Dad needed support
when he was dying, where was she?

296
00:25:35,879 --> 00:25:37,210
Where the hell was she?

297
00:25:37,281 --> 00:25:40,978
You know where she was.
She was right there in the apartment.

298
00:25:41,051 --> 00:25:42,609
Hiding out in the guest room.

299
00:25:42,686 --> 00:25:45,678
She fell apart, okay? People do!

300
00:25:45,756 --> 00:25:47,587
Goddamn it! You were there!

301
00:25:48,926 --> 00:25:50,416
You didn't fall apart.

302
00:25:51,395 --> 00:25:55,627
You heard him calling for her at night.
I had to plead with her to go to him.

303
00:25:55,699 --> 00:25:59,863
Tell me, Dr. Sommers, when people aren't
as strong as you'd like them to be...

304
00:25:59,937 --> 00:26:03,065
...and they let you down,
have you ever considered forgiving them?

305
00:26:16,053 --> 00:26:17,213
I'm sorry, Leslie.

306
00:26:17,287 --> 00:26:18,982
Perfect. Just perfect.

307
00:26:23,127 --> 00:26:24,355
It's okay.

308
00:26:25,229 --> 00:26:27,663
- I'll take you home.
- I brought her, I'll take her.

309
00:26:27,731 --> 00:26:30,427
This whole thing was my idea!
I'll take her home.

310
00:26:30,501 --> 00:26:33,868
No, thank you. I'll take myself home.

311
00:26:35,372 --> 00:26:37,135
I've got to call my mother.

312
00:27:07,371 --> 00:27:09,032
You never answered my question.

313
00:27:09,106 --> 00:27:11,438
I don't have to answer your damn question.

314
00:27:11,508 --> 00:27:15,000
I've considered forgiving Mother
many times. I almost did many times.

315
00:27:15,112 --> 00:27:16,579
"Almost" isn't good enough.

316
00:27:16,647 --> 00:27:18,274
Why the hell not?

317
00:27:18,982 --> 00:27:22,645
"Almost" is good enough for everything
else in this family, isn't it, Davie?

318
00:27:22,719 --> 00:27:24,311
Excuse me, David.

319
00:27:38,468 --> 00:27:40,197
It's all computerized.

320
00:27:40,804 --> 00:27:43,602
The speed will increase.
The grade will increase.

321
00:27:44,007 --> 00:27:45,736
You'll go into oxygen debt.

322
00:27:45,809 --> 00:27:48,801
If you last long enough,
you'll go into oxygen bankruptcy.

323
00:27:48,879 --> 00:27:50,346
Don't worry about it.

324
00:27:50,414 --> 00:27:53,110
I just want to go one second longer
than Marcus.

325
00:27:53,350 --> 00:27:57,116
You do? Marcus holds the institute record
with 25 minutes...

326
00:27:58,322 --> 00:27:59,880
...and 14 seconds.

327
00:27:59,990 --> 00:28:01,184
- Are you ready?
- Yes.

328
00:28:01,258 --> 00:28:02,520
There's your clock.

329
00:28:02,593 --> 00:28:03,958
Have a good trip.

330
00:28:19,610 --> 00:28:21,635
This is the torture test?

331
00:29:25,809 --> 00:29:27,299
He's going for 25.

332
00:29:34,284 --> 00:29:35,581
Come on, David!

333
00:30:02,179 --> 00:30:04,204
Come on, David. Keep it up!

334
00:30:11,822 --> 00:30:13,483
Keep it up! Keep it up!

335
00:30:17,794 --> 00:30:19,421
Come on, David! Push harder!

336
00:31:00,570 --> 00:31:02,629
Come on, David! Keep it up!

337
00:31:08,812 --> 00:31:10,040
Turn it off.

338
00:31:48,685 --> 00:31:50,983
<i>It's like Star Wars down here.</i>

339
00:31:52,856 --> 00:31:54,289
Warp speed.

340
00:33:21,044 --> 00:33:24,036
I can't believe you're still planning
to go to Colorado.

341
00:33:24,114 --> 00:33:28,107
I'll go if David wants to go with me.
He's always wanted to see the West.

342
00:33:28,351 --> 00:33:30,478
- You've got to tell him.
- I can't.

343
00:33:33,957 --> 00:33:35,083
Not now.

344
00:33:35,559 --> 00:33:38,926
Not after what he did today.
I don't want to ruin it for him.

345
00:33:39,930 --> 00:33:41,830
I love him too much for that.

346
00:33:42,198 --> 00:33:43,597
I understand.

347
00:33:44,200 --> 00:33:45,895
I got to run, buddy.

348
00:33:46,236 --> 00:33:48,431
Wait up, I'll walk out with you.

349
00:34:13,763 --> 00:34:14,923
No big deal.

350
00:34:38,021 --> 00:34:39,545
What are you doing out here?

351
00:34:39,623 --> 00:34:41,215
I just needed some fresh air.

352
00:34:41,291 --> 00:34:43,919
I've been looking all over the place for you.

353
00:34:44,761 --> 00:34:47,855
- Want to hear the results?
- I know the results.

354
00:34:48,031 --> 00:34:49,965
You do? Who told you?

355
00:34:50,033 --> 00:34:51,625
Nobody has to tell me.

356
00:34:54,938 --> 00:34:56,030
I'm fine, right?

357
00:34:56,706 --> 00:34:58,139
Physically, you're fine.

358
00:34:58,441 --> 00:35:01,672
You have the cardiovascular system
of King Kong's first cousin.

359
00:35:01,745 --> 00:35:03,440
Just emotionally, you're a mess.

360
00:35:03,913 --> 00:35:07,440
Frankly, anybody who wastes
the potential you've got pisses me off.

361
00:35:07,517 --> 00:35:09,178
Well, it pisses me off, too.

362
00:35:09,853 --> 00:35:13,220
- What are you going to do about it?
- I don't know.

363
00:35:16,192 --> 00:35:20,424
Shinto philosophy teaches you
to accept life as a seasonal occupation.

364
00:35:20,563 --> 00:35:22,861
Sounds like bull Shinto to me.

365
00:35:24,701 --> 00:35:26,635
I burned your ass on the treadmill.

366
00:35:26,703 --> 00:35:29,001
Sure, you also beat my SAT scores.

367
00:35:29,072 --> 00:35:32,132
You're great at taking tests
every few years.

368
00:35:36,379 --> 00:35:38,939
Here's the thing, Shinto.

369
00:35:40,750 --> 00:35:43,275
There's this bike race in Colorado...

370
00:35:43,353 --> 00:35:44,945
The Hell of the West.

371
00:35:46,356 --> 00:35:50,019
- It's the last time I'll race in it and I'd like...
- I'd love to.

372
00:35:50,193 --> 00:35:51,820
- What?
- Race.

373
00:35:52,162 --> 00:35:54,653
Give me a break.
I'm trying to talk you into it.

374
00:35:54,731 --> 00:35:57,859
I had a speech prepared
about how we've never raced together...

375
00:35:57,934 --> 00:36:01,165
...and this might be our last chance,
the Sommers team...

376
00:36:02,205 --> 00:36:04,196
- There's just one thing.
- What?

377
00:36:04,274 --> 00:36:06,242
I'm not shaving my legs.

378
00:36:10,380 --> 00:36:12,143
We'll talk about it.

379
00:36:13,783 --> 00:36:17,014
I think we should give Mom a call.
What do you think?

380
00:36:18,488 --> 00:36:19,455
Okay.

381
00:36:26,529 --> 00:36:28,497
Marcus? How is he?

382
00:36:28,765 --> 00:36:30,562
<i>- He's just fine.
- He is?</i>

383
00:36:30,633 --> 00:36:31,964
Clean as a whistle.

384
00:36:32,035 --> 00:36:33,161
Oh, God!

385
00:36:36,139 --> 00:36:37,470
Oh, darling.

386
00:36:39,142 --> 00:36:41,633
Enough already.
You're supposed to be celebrating.

387
00:36:41,711 --> 00:36:44,009
Oh, darling, I am celebrating.

388
00:36:44,948 --> 00:36:48,406
It's just that I have lived with this
for so long and he's all I've got.

389
00:36:49,252 --> 00:36:51,345
I thought you had two sons.

390
00:36:52,489 --> 00:36:53,922
Marcus, of course I do.

391
00:36:55,592 --> 00:36:58,493
<i>That's not what I was going to say.
Marcus, come on.</i>

392
00:36:58,595 --> 00:36:59,994
That's all right.

393
00:37:00,196 --> 00:37:03,063
This whole conversation is probably not
what I meant to say.

394
00:37:03,967 --> 00:37:05,161
What does that mean?

395
00:37:06,770 --> 00:37:08,260
Davie's all right, isn't he?

396
00:37:08,338 --> 00:37:10,966
Davie's just fine. He sends his love.

397
00:37:12,242 --> 00:37:13,266
I've got to go.

398
00:37:13,343 --> 00:37:16,437
Marcus, I want you to know...
Please understand, I love...

399
00:37:16,513 --> 00:37:17,980
I've got to go.

400
00:37:18,214 --> 00:37:19,181
'Bye.

401
00:37:24,888 --> 00:37:25,718
How's Mom?

402
00:37:25,822 --> 00:37:28,518
- She's fine.
- You told her I was okay, right?

403
00:37:28,825 --> 00:37:30,793
Is this a fish burger in here?

404
00:37:30,994 --> 00:37:34,430
No. I told her you got hit by a bus.
What do you think I told her?

405
00:37:34,497 --> 00:37:36,965
- I want to show you something.
- Where are we going?

406
00:37:41,738 --> 00:37:43,171
Remember this?

407
00:37:43,640 --> 00:37:46,370
This is the first of three stages in this race.

408
00:37:46,442 --> 00:37:50,139
The field gets cut in half here.
If you don't finish in the top half...

409
00:37:50,446 --> 00:37:51,708
...you're out.

410
00:38:01,124 --> 00:38:02,887
- Pretty fast, huh?
- Yeah.

411
00:38:03,526 --> 00:38:05,016
Well, it gets faster.

412
00:38:05,094 --> 00:38:08,325
Coming in the back,
some guys will hit 60 miles an hour.

413
00:38:09,299 --> 00:38:11,494
It can get really dangerous.

414
00:38:13,903 --> 00:38:16,064
There's me and Muzzin going at it.

415
00:38:17,407 --> 00:38:19,671
That's the guy on the poster in the kitchen.

416
00:38:20,944 --> 00:38:24,710
That's Barry Muzzin.
He was my teammate. My best friend.

417
00:38:28,384 --> 00:38:30,545
He's affectionately known
as "the Cannibal."

418
00:38:30,620 --> 00:38:31,780
You know him?

419
00:38:31,855 --> 00:38:33,982
Yes. I was married to him.

420
00:38:36,125 --> 00:38:37,285
Did you see that?

421
00:38:37,360 --> 00:38:38,349
See what?

422
00:38:47,871 --> 00:38:48,860
Right there.

423
00:38:52,175 --> 00:38:54,040
Did you see that? The race is over.

424
00:38:55,111 --> 00:38:55,941
I quit.

425
00:38:56,713 --> 00:38:57,680
You didn't.

426
00:38:57,747 --> 00:39:01,183
Shows you how good I am at it.
Nobody can even tell anymore.

427
00:39:06,189 --> 00:39:08,555
That's what it looks like when you win.

428
00:39:13,396 --> 00:39:15,193
This is what it sounds like.

429
00:40:32,875 --> 00:40:34,001
Two points.

430
00:40:37,413 --> 00:40:38,505
Good shot.

431
00:41:14,684 --> 00:41:16,914
I'm starved. What have you got?

432
00:41:16,986 --> 00:41:19,978
- Give her one of these. They're great.
- Here, Beck.

433
00:41:21,357 --> 00:41:23,655
I'm tired of granola and sesame seeds.

434
00:41:23,893 --> 00:41:27,795
Sesame seeds are great. Pure protein
and energy. It's just what you need.

435
00:41:27,864 --> 00:41:31,698
I need a chocolate shake and french fries.
And a Quarter Pounder with cheese.

436
00:41:31,768 --> 00:41:33,531
Becky, that's flesh.

437
00:41:33,669 --> 00:41:36,502
Have you ever looked in a cow's eyes
when it's killed?

438
00:41:36,572 --> 00:41:39,541
You're eating fear, Becky.
You're becoming one with fear.

439
00:41:39,609 --> 00:41:41,770
We were going to live off the land.

440
00:41:41,844 --> 00:41:46,474
I don't see how eating generic nuts
from the supermarket is living off the land.

441
00:41:46,549 --> 00:41:47,982
We made a vow.

442
00:41:49,318 --> 00:41:52,378
Look into the crystal light
and release meat.

443
00:41:54,557 --> 00:41:56,354
I can't believe this.

444
00:41:58,061 --> 00:41:59,289
What the hell's that?

445
00:41:59,829 --> 00:42:01,421
The Pony Express?

446
00:42:18,548 --> 00:42:20,072
<i>I was wondering...</i>

447
00:42:21,617 --> 00:42:23,084
<i>If Dad were alive today...</i>

448
00:42:23,152 --> 00:42:24,176
<i>Yeah?</i>

449
00:42:24,720 --> 00:42:29,020
Well, they didn't have any cure
for a berry aneurysm two years ago...

450
00:42:29,158 --> 00:42:31,683
- I was wondering...
- They still don't.

451
00:42:32,395 --> 00:42:36,229
If there's a weak blood vessel
and it's located deep inside the brain...

452
00:42:36,299 --> 00:42:40,429
...you can't get to it without destroying
the patient's vital brain functions.

453
00:42:40,503 --> 00:42:43,734
Meaning the patient could become
a chef's salad.

454
00:42:45,641 --> 00:42:47,506
It's like a heart attack of the head.

455
00:42:47,577 --> 00:42:51,741
Even if you're in the best shape,
it can still hit you right out of the blue.

456
00:42:52,949 --> 00:42:56,749
The thing is, you know,
you read those stories...

457
00:42:57,386 --> 00:43:01,345
Some bald guy grows hair again.
Now he needs a haircut once a week.

458
00:43:01,557 --> 00:43:05,049
People doing things through willpower.
What do you think of that stuff?

459
00:43:19,775 --> 00:43:21,003
Good night.

460
00:43:21,611 --> 00:43:23,010
Good night, David.

461
00:43:42,498 --> 00:43:44,625
I always wanted to do that.

462
00:44:06,556 --> 00:44:08,581
Don't forget the napkins.

463
00:44:10,092 --> 00:44:11,719
Can I take your order, please?

464
00:44:11,794 --> 00:44:16,424
I'd like a Quarter Pounder,
large fries and a chocolate shake, please.

465
00:44:17,266 --> 00:44:20,702
It'll be a minute for your Quarter Pounder.
How about a Big Mac?

466
00:44:20,770 --> 00:44:21,668
Okay.

467
00:44:22,638 --> 00:44:24,037
Wait. No.

468
00:44:26,275 --> 00:44:27,105
I'll wait.

469
00:44:51,100 --> 00:44:52,328
Where are you headed?

470
00:44:53,603 --> 00:44:54,661
California maybe.

471
00:44:56,706 --> 00:44:58,003
- You?
- Colorado.

472
00:45:00,710 --> 00:45:02,302
Where are your friends?

473
00:45:02,378 --> 00:45:04,812
It didn't work out. I split.

474
00:45:07,984 --> 00:45:09,918
It isn't right, Marcus.

475
00:45:10,253 --> 00:45:11,015
What?

476
00:45:11,087 --> 00:45:13,647
You should tell him the truth, that's what.

477
00:45:14,657 --> 00:45:17,592
We wouldn't be making this trip
if he knew the truth.

478
00:45:17,660 --> 00:45:21,221
- I think you underestimate him.
- Do you mind? He's my brother!

479
00:45:24,333 --> 00:45:26,995
Maybe I know some things about him
you don't.

480
00:45:27,103 --> 00:45:30,129
Maybe so, but don't use
that tone of voice with me.

481
00:45:33,709 --> 00:45:37,406
- You never heard of bike racing?
- No. Is that what you were doing today?

482
00:45:37,480 --> 00:45:40,711
No, that? We were just training
for this big race in Colorado.

483
00:45:40,783 --> 00:45:44,776
We'll ride to the top of the Rockies
and back. It's very dangerous stuff.

484
00:45:44,854 --> 00:45:48,847
One wrong move and you're just
another statistic in the Hell of the West.

485
00:45:49,125 --> 00:45:50,820
I hope you come out of it alive.

486
00:45:54,130 --> 00:45:54,960
Good luck.

487
00:45:55,197 --> 00:45:56,357
You, too.

488
00:46:03,139 --> 00:46:04,436
Would you like a ride?

489
00:46:08,210 --> 00:46:09,768
Where, on your handlebars?

490
00:46:12,848 --> 00:46:13,906
Marcus, look.

491
00:46:14,016 --> 00:46:15,449
How fast do you go?

492
00:46:16,152 --> 00:46:18,086
Sixty. Sometimes faster.

493
00:46:22,525 --> 00:46:23,924
Hope she's the quiet type.

494
00:46:23,993 --> 00:46:26,985
Not a chance. She even walks loudly.

495
00:46:29,465 --> 00:46:31,990
What did she do to her hair? What is that?

496
00:46:32,735 --> 00:46:34,430
This is Becky Chandler.

497
00:46:34,670 --> 00:46:36,467
Becky, this is my brother, Marcus.

498
00:46:36,539 --> 00:46:38,530
- This is Sarah.
- Hi. Nice to meet you.

499
00:46:38,607 --> 00:46:40,006
How's your finger?

500
00:46:41,977 --> 00:46:43,501
Sorry about that.

501
00:46:43,612 --> 00:46:47,070
Thanks for the ride. Hell of the West, huh?
Sounds great.

502
00:47:08,404 --> 00:47:10,702
How far are you planning to go with us?

503
00:47:10,840 --> 00:47:14,207
Tell you what, Doc.
I'll go pretty far if it feels good.

504
00:47:16,912 --> 00:47:18,004
All right.

505
00:47:50,279 --> 00:47:54,340
Ready? I'll get you on a machine
and have you buffed up in no time.

506
00:47:54,817 --> 00:47:57,012
I don't like this place. It smells bad.

507
00:47:57,086 --> 00:48:00,351
That's sweat, Randolph.
And it does not smell bad.

508
00:48:00,689 --> 00:48:03,089
Mama said I didn't have to do this.

509
00:48:03,426 --> 00:48:05,826
You're in Daddy's sinister clutches now.

510
00:48:05,928 --> 00:48:09,887
And Daddy wants to see his beloved son
Randolph sweat his ass off.

511
00:48:09,965 --> 00:48:11,694
<i>Dr. Conrad, Line 3.</i>

512
00:48:11,767 --> 00:48:13,667
I'll put you on this bike.

513
00:48:14,470 --> 00:48:16,199
Use this one, Randolph.

514
00:48:19,108 --> 00:48:20,132
Hello?

515
00:48:22,411 --> 00:48:24,106
Who is this, please?

516
00:48:24,780 --> 00:48:26,179
How do you do?

517
00:48:26,348 --> 00:48:30,045
It's just that I called his house last night
and then again this morning...

518
00:48:30,119 --> 00:48:32,212
...and no one answered, so...

519
00:48:32,354 --> 00:48:35,289
...being a hysterical person,
I started to worry.

520
00:48:35,357 --> 00:48:37,689
There's nothing to worry about,
Mrs. Sommers.

521
00:48:37,760 --> 00:48:41,662
The three of them went on a camping trip.
Marcus, David and Sarah.

522
00:48:42,164 --> 00:48:43,324
Who is Sarah?

523
00:48:43,399 --> 00:48:45,333
<i>The girl he lives with.</i>

524
00:48:48,170 --> 00:48:49,933
I wanted to tell him something...

525
00:48:50,906 --> 00:48:52,066
<i>... but it can wait.</i>

526
00:48:53,776 --> 00:48:55,971
Come on, Randolph. Move it.

527
00:48:57,346 --> 00:48:59,473
I'll have him call you when he gets back.

528
00:49:00,349 --> 00:49:02,613
You can go faster than that, damn it.

529
00:49:02,685 --> 00:49:05,813
It was nice "meeting you," Mrs. Sommers.

530
00:49:09,024 --> 00:49:11,959
You're supposed to be picking a sport.
So, pick a sport.

531
00:49:12,194 --> 00:49:13,218
I like bowling.

532
00:49:13,295 --> 00:49:18,255
Bowling? Bowling is not a sport.
Bowling is just a big video game.

533
00:49:18,467 --> 00:49:20,094
Don't get all defrosted, Dad.

534
00:49:20,769 --> 00:49:21,861
Don't do what?

535
00:49:21,937 --> 00:49:24,269
You heard me. Don't get all defrosted.

536
00:49:24,340 --> 00:49:26,205
How does your mother put up with you?

537
00:49:26,275 --> 00:49:30,439
Now, look, Dad. The way I see it,
there are no black bowlers.

538
00:49:31,113 --> 00:49:34,947
Basketball, yes. Football, yes.
Golf, we got one guy.

539
00:49:35,751 --> 00:49:38,549
But bowling, we got zip. Think about it.

540
00:49:41,724 --> 00:49:44,022
Boy, bring your ass over here.

541
00:49:45,794 --> 00:49:48,786
We stayed in this same place
two years ago. Remember?

542
00:49:49,031 --> 00:49:51,363
- What do you think?
- I think you better remember.

543
00:49:51,433 --> 00:49:54,664
I think you ought to use
a different tone of voice with me.

544
00:49:54,737 --> 00:49:57,205
It's just the way my parents are.
They're too nice.

545
00:49:57,306 --> 00:50:00,070
I bring a guy home
and they fall in love with him.

546
00:50:00,142 --> 00:50:03,737
So there were three guys I broke up with,
hanging around my house...

547
00:50:03,846 --> 00:50:07,304
...watching TV with my dad,
eating my mom's cookies...

548
00:50:07,883 --> 00:50:09,248
So I freaked out.

549
00:50:09,451 --> 00:50:12,511
That's what I do.
When in doubt, I freak out.

550
00:50:13,722 --> 00:50:16,316
You must fall in love easily. Three guys?

551
00:50:16,392 --> 00:50:17,916
Oh, that wasn't love.

552
00:50:18,694 --> 00:50:20,184
Not love love.

553
00:50:21,397 --> 00:50:23,695
I knew it was going to be like that.

554
00:50:24,533 --> 00:50:26,194
I think she's kind of nice.

555
00:50:26,268 --> 00:50:28,463
What does it say on that T-shirt?

556
00:50:30,806 --> 00:50:33,240
- That's Latin.
- Latin? What does it say?

557
00:50:37,212 --> 00:50:39,407
"Once you've got it up, keep it up."

558
00:50:40,883 --> 00:50:42,612
All right! Where can I get one?

559
00:50:54,096 --> 00:50:57,532
- Let's do it like they do it in the Olympics.
- How do they do it?

560
00:50:57,633 --> 00:50:59,828
You know, exchange T-shirts.

561
00:51:08,677 --> 00:51:09,837
What are you doing?

562
00:51:10,245 --> 00:51:13,612
If it's the Olympics,
you have to play the national anthem.

563
00:51:16,385 --> 00:51:17,909
Only if you win.

564
00:51:19,355 --> 00:51:21,880
Excuse me. You're not going to see that.

565
00:51:31,166 --> 00:51:33,134
So, about that tone of voice...

566
00:51:59,028 --> 00:52:00,120
<i>What's going on?</i>

567
00:52:00,195 --> 00:52:01,219
Shake and break.

568
00:52:01,296 --> 00:52:02,263
What's that?

569
00:52:02,398 --> 00:52:06,061
If you're making a solo breakaway
and you've got a wheel sucker hangin' on...

570
00:52:06,135 --> 00:52:08,695
...you shake and break to shake him off.

571
00:52:09,004 --> 00:52:10,938
<i>Wheel sucker? What's a wheel sucker?</i>

572
00:52:11,006 --> 00:52:12,837
<i>Someone who drafts all the time...</i>

573
00:52:12,908 --> 00:52:15,206
...and won't take his turn up front.

574
00:52:21,083 --> 00:52:23,278
Hey, you wheel sucker!

575
00:52:23,419 --> 00:52:24,613
Get up there!

576
00:52:32,327 --> 00:52:33,692
You want to get them?

577
00:53:06,328 --> 00:53:08,057
We got them! We got them!

578
00:53:22,277 --> 00:53:23,642
Watch this, Dave.

579
00:53:25,080 --> 00:53:26,445
Give it a race, guys.

580
00:53:26,615 --> 00:53:28,845
You boys ought to get yourselves a horse.

581
00:53:38,861 --> 00:53:40,852
Oldest trick in the book, Dave.

582
00:53:51,807 --> 00:53:53,104
That was great.

583
00:54:00,249 --> 00:54:02,012
Second oldest trick in the book.

584
00:54:03,218 --> 00:54:04,685
Look at those buns.

585
00:54:11,326 --> 00:54:12,554
<i>What is that?</i>

586
00:54:13,028 --> 00:54:14,928
<i>Looks like we've got a flat.</i>

587
00:54:43,192 --> 00:54:44,318
We've got to stop.

588
00:54:50,299 --> 00:54:51,391
It's okay.

589
00:54:52,034 --> 00:54:52,932
Sarah!

590
00:54:53,001 --> 00:54:53,933
Jerome!

591
00:54:54,002 --> 00:54:56,334
- Look at you.
- How are you doing?

592
00:54:57,940 --> 00:54:59,931
- It's good to see you.
- It's good seeing you.

593
00:55:00,008 --> 00:55:04,172
I said to Jerome, "Jerome,
that sure looks like Marcus's van."

594
00:55:04,913 --> 00:55:06,505
Our old team van.

595
00:55:07,683 --> 00:55:10,083
- Hello, Geronimo.
- Hello, Muzzin.

596
00:55:11,720 --> 00:55:12,709
Where is he?

597
00:55:13,355 --> 00:55:14,344
Riding.

598
00:55:14,723 --> 00:55:18,489
He's great when it comes to training,
but what's he like in the clutch?

599
00:55:18,560 --> 00:55:20,460
You said you wouldn't start nothing.

600
00:55:20,529 --> 00:55:23,293
You know, Jerome,
women are a real mystery.

601
00:55:24,099 --> 00:55:27,000
In bike racing, the best man always wins.

602
00:55:27,536 --> 00:55:31,973
But what is it about some women that
makes them fall for quitters like Marcus?

603
00:55:32,307 --> 00:55:34,241
You know the bigger mystery, Jerome...

604
00:55:34,309 --> 00:55:38,871
...is what makes "some" women ever fall
for a rabid dog like you, Muzzin.

605
00:55:41,783 --> 00:55:44,047
Hey, come on, you two. Cut it out.

606
00:55:45,687 --> 00:55:47,518
You tell him, Sarah.

607
00:55:49,157 --> 00:55:50,556
He knows I'll win.

608
00:55:51,093 --> 00:55:54,460
But you tell him that I'll make him bleed
before I beat him.

609
00:55:54,630 --> 00:55:58,157
I don't deliver messages.
Sometimes I don't even hear them.

610
00:56:00,002 --> 00:56:01,264
He'll quit.

611
00:56:03,205 --> 00:56:07,198
I'll make sure of that.
I'll make him die in the mountains.

612
00:56:11,213 --> 00:56:13,613
Jerome, I consider you a friend.

613
00:56:14,583 --> 00:56:17,950
Would you take this damn Cannibal
out of my face before I kill him?

614
00:56:18,787 --> 00:56:22,587
I'm Jerome. You're a damn Cannibal.
That's a big rock.

615
00:56:23,558 --> 00:56:25,822
Let's get out of here.
We got a race to win.

616
00:56:29,965 --> 00:56:30,954
'Bye, Sarah.

617
00:56:33,869 --> 00:56:37,862
Well, I'll be a Fig Newton!
I'm standing next to a lady with a past.

618
00:56:45,647 --> 00:56:46,705
<i>Then Jerome says:</i>

619
00:56:48,550 --> 00:56:51,018
"I'm Jerome.
You're the goddamn Cannibal...

620
00:56:51,086 --> 00:56:53,611
"...and this is a big rock." So they left.

621
00:56:54,156 --> 00:56:57,387
Sarah was so tough. So cool.
You missed it all.

622
00:56:59,294 --> 00:57:00,921
I'm keeping this rock.

623
00:57:01,463 --> 00:57:03,624
I'm taking this rock to college.

624
00:57:35,063 --> 00:57:36,928
<i>We're seven minutes to the start...</i>

625
00:57:36,999 --> 00:57:39,991
<i>... of the famous Morgul Bismarck stage
of the Hell of the West.</i>

626
00:57:40,068 --> 00:57:42,866
<i>We're getting the race caravan organized
and ready to begin.</i>

627
00:57:42,938 --> 00:57:44,735
<i>Here come some of the press people.</i>

628
00:57:44,806 --> 00:57:48,537
<i>More vehicles coming through.
Team cars, let's keep the roadway clear.</i>

629
00:57:48,610 --> 00:57:53,172
<i>Mexico, Great Britain, Italy,
Norway team cars coming through.</i>

630
00:57:53,248 --> 00:57:56,547
<i>Press people, please report
to your vehicles immediately.</i>

631
00:57:58,286 --> 00:58:00,618
<i>We'd like to introduce to you
some of the riders...</i>

632
00:58:00,689 --> 00:58:05,353
<i>... who will participate in today's event,
beginning with the U.S. National Team.</i>

633
00:58:09,664 --> 00:58:12,292
<i>And ladies and gentlemen,
the Soviet National Team...</i>

634
00:58:12,367 --> 00:58:15,996
<i>... led by the defending Olympic champion,
Sergei Belov.</i>

635
00:58:17,839 --> 00:58:20,774
<i>And finally, ladies and gentlemen,
the 7-Eleven team...</i>

636
00:58:20,842 --> 00:58:25,870
<i>... led by our own 1980 Olympian and
winner of the Hell of the West last year...</i>

637
00:58:25,947 --> 00:58:28,108
<i>... Barry "the Cannibal" Muzzin.</i>

638
00:58:38,527 --> 00:58:40,188
Shake that, Belov.

639
00:58:43,665 --> 00:58:48,102
<i>And now, our honorary starter for today's
Hell of the West, Stage No. 1...</i>

640
00:58:48,336 --> 00:58:52,796
<i>... ladies and gentlemen, the greatest
racing cyclist in the history of the sport...</i>

641
00:58:52,874 --> 00:58:54,637
<i>... Mr. Eddie Merckx.</i>

642
00:58:57,879 --> 00:59:00,643
<i>We will be starting
on the sound of the pistol.</i>

643
00:59:00,816 --> 00:59:02,249
<i>Riders, ready?</i>

644
00:59:03,318 --> 00:59:04,751
<i>Timers, ready?</i>

645
00:59:09,691 --> 00:59:13,559
<i>We're under way,
the Hell of the West, Stage No. 1.</i>

646
00:59:15,630 --> 00:59:17,723
<i>Let's hear it for a big sendoff.</i>

647
00:59:18,200 --> 00:59:21,601
<i>The Hell of the West, Stage No. 1.
We are under way.</i>

648
00:59:27,909 --> 00:59:31,902
<i>This first circuit of the Hell of the West
is the dreaded Morgul Bismarck.</i>

649
00:59:32,180 --> 00:59:35,547
<i>It's a world championship court
which offers little shade...</i>

650
00:59:35,650 --> 00:59:38,175
<i>... steep hills, fast descents...</i>

651
00:59:38,320 --> 00:59:43,257
<i>... and the gut-wrenching climb to the finish
that sits here, atop the devastating Wall.</i>

652
00:59:43,425 --> 00:59:47,156
<i>Riders who have raced here before
seldom look forward to coming back.</i>

653
00:59:47,262 --> 00:59:51,426
<i>And newcomers to a race of this stature,
unused to riding in a large pack...</i>

654
00:59:51,733 --> 00:59:53,325
<i>... will soon find out why.</i>

655
00:59:53,401 --> 00:59:57,201
<i>This is a race of seven laps,
totaling 91 miles.</i>

656
00:59:57,372 --> 00:59:59,602
<i>A grueling test for any rider.</i>

657
01:00:00,175 --> 01:00:01,574
Sommers, look out!

658
01:00:01,776 --> 01:00:03,300
Watch your line!

659
01:00:07,582 --> 01:00:09,573
Move over, Sommers! Move over!

660
01:00:22,864 --> 01:00:24,058
Here we go, Dave.

661
01:00:25,066 --> 01:00:27,296
Enough of this Sunday stroll.

662
01:00:27,669 --> 01:00:29,432
Let's hurt a little bit.

663
01:01:56,625 --> 01:01:58,991
10-4. We are rolling in
an ambulance right now.

664
01:02:09,104 --> 01:02:11,072
<i>Three laps down and four to go.</i>

665
01:02:11,139 --> 01:02:13,699
<i>Four to go, four laps yet to go.</i>

666
01:02:13,775 --> 01:02:17,871
<i>Barry Muzzin in the 7-Eleven team
followed closely by the Soviet team...</i>

667
01:02:17,979 --> 01:02:20,072
<i>... and Marcus Sommers of ShaverSport.</i>

668
01:02:20,148 --> 01:02:24,414
<i>Each lap yet to come on this grueling
course will take its toll on the riders.</i>

669
01:02:24,552 --> 01:02:27,248
<i>Only the toughest will be
among the first 48...</i>

670
01:02:27,389 --> 01:02:31,416
<i>... who will go on to contest Stages 2 and 3
of the Hell of the West.</i>

671
01:02:39,668 --> 01:02:40,635
Shit!

672
01:02:40,969 --> 01:02:42,163
Tough break, Marcus!

673
01:02:43,305 --> 01:02:45,364
Marcus has got a flat. Pull up. Quick.

674
01:02:47,542 --> 01:02:49,669
Okay, pull up. Slow up. Come on.

675
01:02:55,684 --> 01:02:57,174
Come on, Sarah.

676
01:02:57,619 --> 01:03:00,087
Come on, baby, they're leaving us behind.

677
01:03:01,323 --> 01:03:02,620
Come on, honey.

678
01:03:04,626 --> 01:03:07,595
You got it. Good. Good girl. Now, push.

679
01:03:08,430 --> 01:03:09,419
Push.

680
01:03:10,598 --> 01:03:11,587
Look.

681
01:03:17,105 --> 01:03:18,504
Move it! Move it!

682
01:03:18,973 --> 01:03:20,634
Come on! Pick it up!

683
01:03:23,078 --> 01:03:26,275
You want back in this race!
Pick it up! Come on!

684
01:03:26,815 --> 01:03:29,340
<i>One lap to go! Bell lap coming up.</i>

685
01:03:29,417 --> 01:03:31,885
<i>One lap to go! One lap to go!</i>

686
01:03:38,760 --> 01:03:39,749
Here we are!

687
01:03:42,864 --> 01:03:44,161
Here you go!

688
01:03:44,299 --> 01:03:46,699
Marcus, water! You need this.

689
01:03:54,442 --> 01:03:55,704
Water! Water!

690
01:03:55,777 --> 01:03:59,406
You're 52, David. You've got to move up.
You've got to move up!

691
01:04:06,621 --> 01:04:09,146
<i>The caravan is in sight,
ladies and gentlemen.</i>

692
01:04:09,224 --> 01:04:12,159
<i>They are around the corner,
at the bottom of the Wall.</i>

693
01:04:12,293 --> 01:04:13,385
<i>Here they come.</i>

694
01:04:13,461 --> 01:04:17,454
<i>And in a remarkable recovery,
Marcus Sommers has regained position...</i>

695
01:04:17,532 --> 01:04:22,060
<i>... near the front of the lead group
after a flat tire way out on the course.</i>

696
01:04:27,442 --> 01:04:31,378
<i>Muzzin, Sommers and the Soviet, Belov,
fighting it out as they come up the Wall.</i>

697
01:04:31,613 --> 01:04:34,411
<i>A real neck-and-neck battle
as they come through.</i>

698
01:04:43,425 --> 01:04:45,552
<i>It will be a three-way sprint for the first.</i>

699
01:04:45,627 --> 01:04:49,119
<i>The Americans, Sommers and Muzzin,
and the Soviet, Belov.</i>

700
01:04:50,598 --> 01:04:53,192
<i>Right now it's Muzzin in front,
Sommers, second.</i>

701
01:04:53,268 --> 01:04:56,567
<i>Sergei Belov of the Soviet team
charging up in third.</i>

702
01:05:08,817 --> 01:05:11,012
<i>And it's Marcus Sommers, the winner!</i>

703
01:05:11,286 --> 01:05:13,982
<i>Muzzin, second. Sergei Belov, third place.</i>

704
01:05:16,458 --> 01:05:19,052
<i>Ladies and gentlemen,
a tremendous finish!</i>

705
01:05:19,194 --> 01:05:21,788
<i>Sommers, Muzzin and the Soviet, Belov.</i>

706
01:05:40,215 --> 01:05:43,548
<i>Fourteen, 15, 16 riders across the line.</i>

707
01:05:44,052 --> 01:05:48,045
<i>The winners are already in.
We're counting the last riders to qualify.</i>

708
01:05:48,223 --> 01:05:52,387
<i>Only the first 48 finishers today
will be able to race tomorrow.</i>

709
01:05:54,562 --> 01:05:56,826
- Where's David? How far back?
- I don't know.

710
01:05:59,968 --> 01:06:02,630
<i>Only three more riders will stay
in the race.</i>

711
01:06:03,805 --> 01:06:06,365
<i>The rest will have to wait until next year.</i>

712
01:06:11,279 --> 01:06:12,769
- Is that him?
- It is.

713
01:06:24,292 --> 01:06:26,692
<i>With the field closing in fast behind them...</i>

714
01:06:26,761 --> 01:06:29,491
<i>... two riders, the final two
that will qualify...</i>

715
01:06:29,564 --> 01:06:32,260
<i>... and the field is eating them up
coming up the Wall.</i>

716
01:06:33,668 --> 01:06:37,604
<i>Struggling up the Wall for the final time
in this grueling Hell of the West.</i>

717
01:06:37,672 --> 01:06:39,105
<i>And they're down!</i>

718
01:06:43,378 --> 01:06:46,745
<i>One rider is back up.
He's on his bike and he's going to finish.</i>

719
01:06:58,126 --> 01:06:59,115
Run with it!

720
01:06:59,761 --> 01:07:01,228
Get going! Pick it up!

721
01:07:08,403 --> 01:07:10,371
- Can he do that?
- I don't know.

722
01:07:10,538 --> 01:07:11,630
That's it. Run!

723
01:07:16,811 --> 01:07:18,779
Come on, David! A little more!

724
01:07:26,888 --> 01:07:32,758
<i>And in a remarkable finish, David Sommers
crosses the line 48, carrying his bicycle.</i>

725
01:07:33,328 --> 01:07:35,319
- Can he do that?
- Is that legal?

726
01:07:35,797 --> 01:07:37,424
I think I screwed up.

727
01:07:40,001 --> 01:07:40,831
It's okay.

728
01:07:40,902 --> 01:07:42,767
<i>It's official, ladies and gentlemen...</i>

729
01:07:42,837 --> 01:07:46,329
<i>... David Sommers becomes the 48th
and final qualifier...</i>

730
01:07:46,441 --> 01:07:49,274
<i>... to ride Stages 2 and 3
of the Hell of the West.</i>

731
01:07:51,245 --> 01:07:53,873
- Two more stages.
- It was a real close race, wasn't it?

732
01:07:53,948 --> 01:07:54,846
No shit!

